": \"Consumer Staples\",    \"category\": \"defensive\", \"uptrend_ratio\": 1.0, \"return_1m_pct\": -4.17, \"return_3m_pct\": 0.40  },\n    \"XLU\":  { \"name\": \"Utilities\",           \"category\": \"defensive\", \"uptrend_ratio\": 1.0, \"return_1m_pct\": -1.86, \"return_3m_pct\": 8.24  },\n    \"XLRE\": { \"name\": \"Real Estate\",         \"category\": \"defensive\", \"uptrend_ratio\": 1.0, \"return_1m_pct\": 2.34,  \"return_3m_pct\": 6.46  },\n    \"XLB\":  { \"name\": \"Materials\",           \"category\": \"cyclical\",  \"uptrend_ratio\": 1.0, \"return_1m_pct\": 4.33,  \"return_3m_pct\": 5.76  }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Key findings and methodology notes:**\n\n**Data sources:**\n- `uptrend_ratio_overall` (0.5777) comes directly from the TraderMonty CSV (`Breadth_Index_Raw` — ratio of S&P 500 stocks above their 200-day MA, as of 2026-04-14). The CSV does not provide per-sector uptrend breakdowns, so per-sector `uptrend_ratio` is a binary ETF-level proxy (1.0 = ETF price above its own 200-day MA, 0.0 = below). XLF is the only sector ETF currently below its 200-day MA.\n\n**Rotation signal — `cyclical_leading`:**\n- Cyclicals are outperforming defensives by a wide margin on 1-month basis (+3.72% vs -1.44%) and modestly on 3-month (+3.48% vs +2.37%).\n- Leading cyclicals: XLK (+7.46%), XLF (+6.31%), XLY (+5.47%), XLB (+4.33%).\n- Lagging defensives: XLP (-4.17%), XLV (-2.05%), XLU (-1.86%).\n\n**Cycle positioning — `recovery_bounce`:**\n- Overall breadth at 57.8% is moderate (not strongly bullish), the 200-day MA trend is negative (`Breadth_200MA_Trend = -1`) with a bearish signal still active, but the shorter 50-day MA trend has flipped positive. This combination suggests a bounce within a broader corrective structure rather than confirmed new-bull expansion.\n\n**Caution flag:** XLE is a notable outlier — strong 3-month return (+19.64%) but weak 1-month (-2.88%), suggesting energy had a big move earlier but is now rolling over."}],"totalDurationMs":68309,"tota